00:31:38.660 --> 00:31:44.040
in your own writing, you know, your
characters become who they want,

00:31:44.040 --> 00:31:46.290
who you want them to be
and then they take off

00:31:46.290 --> 00:31:47.590
on a life of their own.

00:31:47.590 --> 00:31:48.890
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: That's true.

00:31:48.890 --> 00:31:51.410
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: So my
next question is who

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:54.840
or what are the major
influences on your work?

00:31:54.840 --> 00:31:58.540
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: It's
difficult to say.

00:32:01.770 --> 00:32:04.070
There's so many.

00:32:05.780 --> 00:32:10.720
I love, it's a strange thing
because I write in French,

00:32:10.720 --> 00:32:13.560
my two mother tongues are
French and Creole so I write

00:32:13.560 --> 00:32:16.070
in French and originally Creole.

00:32:16.070 --> 00:32:17.400
I don't write in English,

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:24.990
I don't know if I should say
unfortunately or anyway not yet.

00:32:24.990 --> 00:32:32.350
But I find that [Inaudible] has
been very, very inspiring for me

00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:35.110
because in [Inaudible]
I find the vitality

00:32:35.110 --> 00:32:37.630
that I don't find in [inaudible].

00:32:37.630 --> 00:32:42.440
But he has much more freedom
and [inaudible] with language

00:32:42.440 --> 00:32:47.150
in [inaudible] than
French literature.

00:32:47.150 --> 00:32:48.580
[Inaudible] nowadays.

00:32:48.580 --> 00:32:53.900
And so I've read a lot of
[Inaudible] and I particularly

00:32:53.900 --> 00:32:59.750
like authors like [Inaudible]
who could create,

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:02.010
and I was always fascinated

00:33:02.010 --> 00:33:09.400
by that person who's
totally not alive at all.

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:13.770
It's ink on a white page and
then suddenly just by the way,

00:33:13.770 --> 00:33:17.750
a word here instead of here,
a comma here instead of there,

00:33:17.750 --> 00:33:22.520
you create a world and you create
characters who become like persons

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:24.970
and feel like they're alive
and not until you've put

00:33:24.970 --> 00:33:29.080
down the book you have impression
that its characters are walking

00:33:29.080 --> 00:33:33.800
with you and still be
with you years and years.

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:36.620
And he knows how [inaudible]
creates characters

00:33:36.620 --> 00:33:40.760
that you know wouldn't exist
in real life but in the spirits

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:43.670
of the book are really, are alive.

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:47.460
And Salman Rushdie was [inaudible].

00:33:47.460 --> 00:33:54.440
"Midnight's Children" for me is
one of these books that really says

00:33:54.440 --> 00:33:57.980
so much about the power of
literature to create a world

00:33:57.980 --> 00:34:05.260
and to create people that go
beyond what we could experience but

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:11.860
yet tell us so much about who we
are and our place in the world.

00:34:15.850 --> 00:34:17.150
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: All right.

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:18.750
My next question for
you, why did you choose

00:34:18.750 --> 00:34:21.490
to write fiction as
your creative outlet.

00:34:21.490 --> 00:34:24.810
I know you've written short
stories, plays, and news articles,

00:34:24.810 --> 00:34:28.910
but also have you delved into
other literary genres like poetry?

00:34:32.300 --> 00:34:33.600
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: We
have a discussion,

00:34:33.600 --> 00:34:34.900
it's fun that you ask the question

00:34:34.900 --> 00:34:37.640
because we have an
ongoing discussion

00:34:37.640 --> 00:34:41.830
about that for the past two months.

00:34:41.830 --> 00:34:46.590
I've never dared poetry because
I love poetry so much and I felt

00:34:46.590 --> 00:34:50.590
like it was higher than me.

00:34:50.590 --> 00:34:53.140
But then I've been writing
something since I've been here

00:34:53.140 --> 00:34:57.410
and I've been writing in English
which for me is quite strange.

00:34:57.410 --> 00:34:59.900
And my friends [inaudible]
tell me that,

00:34:59.900 --> 00:35:01.980
"You're writing poems,"
and I said, "No.

00:35:01.980 --> 00:35:03.280
I'm not writing poems.

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:04.680
I'm writing text."

00:35:04.680 --> 00:35:08.870
But I'm a little bit surprised
about the categorizations we make.

00:35:08.870 --> 00:35:13.650
If it's creative non-fiction, or
fiction, or poetry, or novellas,

00:35:13.650 --> 00:35:18.750
or short stories, or for
me all these are texts.

00:35:18.750 --> 00:35:23.430
And the [inaudible] is not
the genre but the voice.

00:35:23.430 --> 00:35:28.590
What I'm looking for in
text is voice and the story.

00:35:28.590 --> 00:35:34.640
You write if you have a
story to tell, otherwise,

00:35:34.640 --> 00:35:38.670
I mean go play [inaudible].

00:35:38.670 --> 00:35:44.090
There are so many stories
around us that want to be told.

00:35:44.090 --> 00:35:50.850
And I've tried, I like
particularly the short story

00:35:50.850 --> 00:35:56.630
because the short story
for me is like the pebble

00:35:56.630 --> 00:36:01.150
that you throw in a pond.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:02.990
It's very compact.

00:36:02.990 --> 00:36:06.340
It goes down very quickly.

00:36:06.340 --> 00:36:10.240
But it leaves after it these
ripples on the water which are

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:13.300
like echoes that grow around you.

00:36:13.300 --> 00:36:17.090
And a good short story when it's
well written, it's [inaudible].

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:18.790
It's like throwing a
pebble in a pond that gives,

00:36:18.790 --> 00:36:22.600
it stays with you for
long afterwards.

00:36:22.600 --> 00:36:24.950
People like to think that
writing a novel is more difficult

00:36:24.950 --> 00:36:26.250
than writing a short story.

00:36:26.250 --> 00:36:28.410
I don't totally agree.

00:36:28.410 --> 00:36:29.710
It's another process.

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:31.510
It's a longer process.

00:36:31.510 --> 00:36:41.380
But you're not, you can be less
good at some things and try to make

00:36:41.380 --> 00:36:47.120
up for it in other aspects.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:49.040
In a short story you can't.

00:36:49.040 --> 00:36:54.760
Either it's well written
and it's good or it's not.

00:36:54.760 --> 00:36:58.790
And theater, plays is also a
very interesting field for me

00:36:58.790 --> 00:37:00.780
because it's a place where
you're in [inaudible] contact

00:37:00.780 --> 00:37:03.150
with the [inaudible] and
that's very important.

00:37:03.150 --> 00:37:04.890 position:56%
When you write a novel, you write it

00:37:04.890 --> 00:37:06.190
and then you don't
know where it goes.

00:37:06.190 --> 00:37:08.890
You're not in contact
with people who read it

00:37:08.890 --> 00:37:11.700
but you can read it afterwards
but it's not the same process.

00:37:11.700 --> 00:37:19.340
In the plays, writing is
directly aimed at people

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:22.160
so that's a very interesting
thing also.

00:37:22.160 --> 00:37:27.040
I'm also interested in graphic
novels because that's another way.

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:29.450
And in fact, I'm fascinated

00:37:29.450 --> 00:37:33.890
by all the different
ways of telling a story.

00:37:33.890 --> 00:37:39.200
At the IWP in Iowa City we had
an interaction with some dancers

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:41.610
from their school of dance.

00:37:41.610 --> 00:37:46.620 position:56%
And it was really fascinating to
see how they took some of our texts,

00:37:46.620 --> 00:37:52.780
what we got from it and how they
told our story, everybody's,

00:37:52.780 --> 00:37:56.240
so how the stories we write
can be told by others.

00:37:56.240 --> 00:38:01.640
And we see it and felt by other
people and told different view.

00:38:01.640 --> 00:38:05.230
And I think this is [inaudible].

00:38:05.230 --> 00:38:06.530
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: Okay.

00:38:06.530 --> 00:38:10.260
That's really interesting to me
as a writer because I know also

00:38:10.260 --> 00:38:14.120
that it's more difficult to write
a 500 word article than it is

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:16.390
to write a 1500 word article.

00:38:16.390 --> 00:38:20.420
So I think the parallel is there
with the news stories also.

00:38:20.420 --> 00:38:21.720
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: Yes.

00:38:21.720 --> 00:38:23.880
That's one of the first things my
first [inaudible] chief told me

00:38:23.880 --> 00:38:25.610
when I started as a [inaudible].

00:38:25.610 --> 00:38:27.150
I was nineteen.

00:38:27.150 --> 00:38:31.020
And I had been investigating on
something for weeks and weeks

00:38:31.020 --> 00:38:34.230
and I came up with so many
information [inaudible] I kind

00:38:34.230 --> 00:38:36.840
of said, "Can't I have two
pages of the newspaper?"

00:38:36.840 --> 00:38:38.140
And he said, "No.

00:38:38.140 --> 00:38:39.440
You won't.

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:40.740
Just one page and you
stick to that."

00:38:40.740 --> 00:38:42.040
And I said, "There's so
many things to [inaudible]

00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:44.080
that I have to leave aside."

00:38:44.080 --> 00:38:49.380
And he said to me, you know, one
day he went to his editor and chief

00:38:49.380 --> 00:38:56.570
and gave him this article and said,
"[Inaudible] I didn't have time."

00:38:56.570 --> 00:39:01.680
[Inaudible] even more
time to make it short.

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:04.080
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: Okay.

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:06.120
Having been born and
raised in Mauritius,

00:39:06.120 --> 00:39:10.100
and what has Mauritian
literature been like historically

00:39:10.100 --> 00:39:12.780
and what's happening in
the literary scene now?

00:39:15.070 --> 00:39:19.390
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: The actual
literary scene is very active,

00:39:19.390 --> 00:39:21.040
very energetic I would say.

00:39:21.040 --> 00:39:23.490
There have been, Mauritius
published the first book

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:28.030
in the southern hemisphere
in 18-something, I forget

00:39:28.030 --> 00:39:32.590
but in the nineteenth century.

00:39:32.590 --> 00:39:40.680
And since then we have had a
very lively literary scene.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:44.040
There have been different
phases in that.

00:39:44.040 --> 00:39:50.350
At one point we had all that
colonial literature [inaudible],

00:39:50.350 --> 00:39:54.350 position:56%
you know, the breeze in the palm
trees and the beautiful young Creole

00:39:54.350 --> 00:39:58.240
and the verandas and
things like that.

00:39:58.240 --> 00:40:03.910
And [Inaudible] the great French
poet wrote there [inaudible] poem

00:40:03.910 --> 00:40:05.210 position:56%
called [inaudible] for a Creole lady

00:40:05.210 --> 00:40:09.260
which was directly inspired
by these [inaudible]

00:40:09.260 --> 00:40:13.250
when his parents were
sent him away from Paris

00:40:13.250 --> 00:40:19.690
where he was living a very,
how can I say the word?

00:40:19.690 --> 00:40:24.930
They didn't like the life he was
living in Paris, the [inaudible]

00:40:24.930 --> 00:40:28.820
so they were trying to send him
away to India and on his way

00:40:28.820 --> 00:40:30.720
to India the boat stopped
in Mauritius

00:40:30.720 --> 00:40:32.340
and then he never went further.

00:40:32.340 --> 00:40:35.870
He stayed in Mauritius and
then he went back to France

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:39.590
and he wrote these
poems that are part

00:40:39.590 --> 00:40:42.040
of his famous connection
called [Inaudible].

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:43.340
So there has been a lot

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:45.910
of that emotional literature
a few years back.

00:40:45.910 --> 00:40:51.300
And then there has been
a second phase where

00:40:51.300 --> 00:40:55.390
Mauritian writers felt like
they had to exile themselves

00:40:55.390 --> 00:40:58.310
to be able to exist as writers,

00:40:58.310 --> 00:41:00.650
that it wouldn't be happening
in Mauritius so they had to go

00:41:00.650 --> 00:41:05.550 position:56%
to France, or England, and to other
countries like that to be recognized

00:41:05.550 --> 00:41:10.200
as writers either to
live as writers.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:12.730
And suddenly we had a lot
of literature that was kind

00:41:12.730 --> 00:41:26.550
of looking back at the island like
something dreamed and it over -- .

00:41:29.680 --> 00:41:31.070
I can't find the word in English.

00:41:31.070 --> 00:41:32.370
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: Romanticized?

00:41:32.370 --> 00:41:33.670
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: Yeah.

00:41:33.670 --> 00:41:34.970
In a way that's it.

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:39.270 position:56%
But then we have a generation now
of writers who really know Mauritius

00:41:39.270 --> 00:41:46.640
and who talk about Mauritius
in a very different way.

00:41:46.640 --> 00:41:48.780
We have writers, a
generation of writers

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:52.500
who are published mostly in France.

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:56.040
I have a friend writer
called [Inaudible].

00:41:56.040 --> 00:42:02.770
Her latest novel called
[Inaudible] was in line

00:42:02.770 --> 00:42:11.420 position:56%
for the [inaudible] most prestigious
French prizes a few weeks back,

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:13.440
[foreign language spoken].

00:42:13.440 --> 00:42:16.920
And it's interesting to
note that at the same time

00:42:16.920 --> 00:42:20.220
as there is the great
vitality of our writers,

00:42:20.220 --> 00:42:23.720
we are not read now in our country.

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:27.390
We are read elsewhere
around the world and studied

00:42:27.390 --> 00:42:29.430
around the world but
not in our country.

00:42:29.430 --> 00:42:35.400 position:56%
But I think that Mauritians in a
way have a problem with what we tell

00:42:35.400 --> 00:42:39.270
and say in our literature.

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:41.390
When my second book came out
it was, it's called "Sensitive"

00:42:41.390 --> 00:42:44.470
and it was published in France.

00:42:44.470 --> 00:42:46.890
So the news first came
out in the newspapers

00:42:46.890 --> 00:42:51.050
that I was having a book published
in France by a great publisher.

00:42:51.050 --> 00:42:53.130
And so people came up
to me saying, "Wow.

00:42:53.130 --> 00:42:54.430
We are proud.

00:42:54.430 --> 00:42:55.730
That's great."

00:42:55.730 --> 00:42:57.500
[Inaudible] colony so there's
still that tendency, well,

00:42:57.500 --> 00:43:03.400
if it's published over there, it
must be good, it must be great.

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:04.720
And I say, "If it was published

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:06.620
in Mauritius I would have been
writing exactly the same book,"

00:43:06.620 --> 00:43:08.020
but never mind.

00:43:08.020 --> 00:43:10.110
[Laughs]

00:43:10.110 --> 00:43:12.930
Book then the book came out.

00:43:12.930 --> 00:43:18.060
People started reading it and
that's where the problem started.

00:43:18.060 --> 00:43:22.570
I was approached by a
lady once in a bookstore

00:43:22.570 --> 00:43:24.180
when I was doing a book signing.

00:43:24.180 --> 00:43:29.500
And she was very angry and
she was very aggressive.

00:43:29.500 --> 00:43:31.770
And she told me, "Why
did you have to go

00:43:31.770 --> 00:43:35.990
and tell these things
about us in France?"

00:43:35.990 --> 00:43:40.390 position:56%
Because the image of Mauritians that
I did in my book didn't fit at all

00:43:40.390 --> 00:43:42.700
with the postcard image
that we have.

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:49.340
We're a tropical country,
very touristic country.

00:43:49.340 --> 00:43:54.890
We like being told we're the
best, we're the number one,

00:43:54.890 --> 00:43:56.190
[inaudible] for the great.

00:43:56.190 --> 00:43:59.620
And we don't like anything
going against that image.

00:43:59.620 --> 00:44:03.860
And we contemporary writers
are not writing the postcard.

00:44:03.860 --> 00:44:06.790
I don't mean to say we're
writing against the postcard

00:44:06.790 --> 00:44:11.330 position:56%
but what we're telling doesn't quite
go across with the official image.

00:44:11.330 --> 00:44:13.060
And so I told this lady, "Well,

00:44:13.060 --> 00:44:16.940
I'm not here to do the
promotion of Mauritius.

00:44:16.940 --> 00:44:20.230
[Inaudible] all that at the tourist
office and they do a very good job.

00:44:20.230 --> 00:44:24.360
And that's not my job as a writer."

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:29.420 position:56%
But I think we're very much a
culture of representation and that's

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:33.690
about [inaudible] our colonial
past as to our touristic present

00:44:33.690 --> 00:44:38.040
where we don't like things to
go against the official image.

00:44:38.040 --> 00:44:44.570
And that's where we writers
are a bit not going [inaudible]

00:44:44.570 --> 00:44:48.840
but that's the way it is.

00:44:48.840 --> 00:44:50.610
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: Do you have
a favorite Mauritian writer,

00:44:50.610 --> 00:44:51.960
other than yourself?

00:44:51.960 --> 00:44:53.260
[Laughs].

00:44:53.260 --> 00:44:54.560
&gt;&gt; Shenaz Patel: [Laughs].

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:55.860
Nathacha Appanah is a great writer.

00:44:55.860 --> 00:44:58.690
I encourage all of
you to read her books.

00:44:58.690 --> 00:45:01.280
She has a book that
has been translated

00:45:01.280 --> 00:45:03.440
in English that's called
"The Last Brother".

00:45:03.440 --> 00:45:06.410
And it tells the story
of her, you know,

00:45:06.410 --> 00:45:10.520
at one time when the Jews
were leaving Europe to go

00:45:10.520 --> 00:45:14.950
to Palestine during
the Second World War,

00:45:14.950 --> 00:45:19.600
a boat was anchored by the British.

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:26.040
And some of the, there were
1,000, a little over 1,000 Jews

00:45:27.200 --> 00:45:30.070
that they sent to Mauritius.

00:45:30.070 --> 00:45:33.450 position:56%
And so this book tells the encounter
between the young Mauritian boy

00:45:33.450 --> 00:45:38.280
who has lost his brothers in
[inaudible] and a young Jewish boy

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:43.100
who is imprisoned in Mauritius
and it's a beautiful book

00:45:43.100 --> 00:45:45.040
and it's called "The Last Brother."

00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:52.070
There's also [inaudible]
which is a powerful writer.

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:53.940
[Inaudible].

00:45:53.940 --> 00:46:01.730
He wrote a book, a beautiful book
called [Foreign language spoken].

00:46:01.730 --> 00:46:07.060
It's called in English it's "The
House that Walked to [inaudible]".

00:46:07.060 --> 00:46:12.100
And it tells a lot about the inter
ethnic relationships in Mauritius

00:46:12.100 --> 00:46:15.890
and it's really a very
interesting and beautiful book.

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:18.630
&gt;&gt; Eve Ferguson: I believe I
